(<i> muttering</i> )

27
00:03:26,985 --> 00:03:27,815
Is this...

28
00:03:27,819 --> 00:03:29,389
Yes! This is Cragganmore,

29
00:03:29,387 --> 00:03:32,017
and yes, this is
the house of Ulrich,

30
00:03:32,022 --> 00:03:34,222
and no, he
won't see you.

31
00:03:34,224 --> 00:03:35,574
But...

32
00:03:35,574 --> 00:03:36,924
I know-- you've
come a long way.

33
00:03:36,926 --> 00:03:38,226
Your business is urgent.

34
00:03:38,227 --> 00:03:39,587
It doesn't matter.

35
00:03:39,595 --> 00:03:40,855
He sees no one.

36
00:03:40,862 --> 00:03:42,262
Please.
Please

37
00:03:42,263 --> 00:03:43,703
yourself.

38
00:03:43,697 --> 00:03:45,697
Go home.

39
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:50,470
Well, what do we
do now,<i> boy?</i>

40
00:03:50,470 --> 00:03:55,210
You who know so much--
answer me that.

41
00:03:58,277 --> 00:04:02,307
Hear me, you who dwell
in Cragganmore!

42
00:04:02,313 --> 00:04:08,223
Ulrich, we will stay here
until we are heard!

43
00:04:10,485 --> 00:04:13,785
(<i> water dripping</i> )

44
00:04:18,091 --> 00:04:22,331
Magister?

45
00:04:33,672 --> 00:04:35,472
Uh.

46
00:04:36,907 --> 00:04:38,137
What is it?

47
00:04:38,141 --> 00:04:39,911
W-We have visitors.

48
00:04:39,909 --> 00:04:41,639
(<i> water drips</i> )

49
00:04:41,644 --> 00:04:43,644
I know.

50
00:04:43,646 --> 00:04:45,006
I will see them.

51
00:04:45,014 --> 00:04:47,084
You will?

52
00:04:47,082 --> 00:04:48,212
Yes.

53
00:04:48,216 --> 00:04:52,446
There's a great task
needing to be done.

54
00:04:52,453 --> 00:04:55,723
I have been witness
to something.

55
00:04:55,722 --> 00:05:00,662
Something of
consequence to you.

56
00:05:00,659 --> 00:05:01,759
To me?

57
00:05:01,760 --> 00:05:03,930
Yes.

58
00:05:03,928 --> 00:05:06,388
My own death.

59
00:05:08,398 --> 00:05:11,228
(<i> chuckling</i> ):
Yeah, yeah, I knew it.

60
00:05:11,234 --> 00:05:12,334
Thieves.

61
00:05:12,335 --> 00:05:15,295
(<i> muttering</i> )

62
00:05:19,040 --> 00:05:21,970
(<i> bird squawks</i> )

63
00:05:22,875 --> 00:05:25,975
(<i> squawking</i> )

64
00:05:28,713 --> 00:05:32,923
Looks forbidding enough,
don't you think?

65
00:05:32,917 --> 00:05:34,817
Oh, yes.

66
00:05:34,818 --> 00:05:37,148
Master?

67
00:05:37,153 --> 00:05:38,393
No.

68
00:05:38,387 --> 00:05:42,517
They'd think me infirm.

69
00:05:42,523 --> 00:05:47,733
Bellasarius wore this
before<i> he</i> died.

70
00:05:47,727 --> 00:05:54,297
You know, I actually saw him
change lead into gold.

71
00:05:55,267 --> 00:05:57,127
I could never do that.

72
00:05:57,135 --> 00:05:58,425
Hmm. Too bad.

73
00:05:58,436 --> 00:06:01,766
You'd have stood
to inherit some<i> real</i> wealth.

74
00:06:01,772 --> 00:06:05,312
Magister, please don't talk
like that.

75
00:06:05,308 --> 00:06:07,208
You're not going to die.

76
00:06:07,209 --> 00:06:10,139
Oh, but I look forward to it.

77
00:06:10,145 --> 00:06:11,875
All this magic--

78
00:06:11,880 --> 00:06:15,180
what has it accomplished?

79
00:06:15,183 --> 00:06:17,923
Tell me,
how are your studies going?

80
00:06:17,919 --> 00:06:19,619
(<i> bird squawking</i> )

81
00:06:19,620 --> 00:06:21,090
Fine.

82
00:06:21,088 --> 00:06:22,318
They're going well.

83
00:06:22,322 --> 00:06:25,422
You still wish
to be a sorcerer?

84
00:06:25,425 --> 00:06:27,315
Oh, yes, more
than anything.

85
00:06:27,326 --> 00:06:30,086
Hmm. Well, then...
(<i> speaks Latin</i> )

86
00:06:30,095 --> 00:06:35,865
get yourself a handful of that
sulphurous ash over there.

87
00:06:55,585 --> 00:06:59,585
(<i> vibrating whir</i> )

88
00:07:09,030 --> 00:07:12,430
(<i> chants spell</i> )

89
00:07:18,604 --> 00:07:22,074
(<i> flames roaring</i> )

90
00:07:30,048 --> 00:07:32,148
Welcome to Cragganmore.

91
00:07:32,150 --> 00:07:33,550
I am Ulrich.

92
00:07:33,551 --> 00:07:38,551
Which of you men
calls himself Valerian?

93
00:07:40,356 --> 00:07:41,686
We are here on behalf...

94
00:07:41,690 --> 00:07:43,960
I know why you are here.

95
00:07:43,958 --> 00:07:45,588
You're a delegation...

96
00:07:45,592 --> 00:07:50,092
from Urland,
which is beyond Valvasia.

97
00:07:51,263 --> 00:07:54,733
Let's see the artifacts.

98
00:08:07,278 --> 00:08:09,378
Scales.

99
00:08:09,380 --> 00:08:11,780
How did you come by these?

100
00:08:11,782 --> 00:08:12,582
I found them

101
00:08:12,582 --> 00:08:15,722
at the mouth
of the lair.

102
00:08:16,517 --> 00:08:19,177
What else?

103
00:08:22,255 --> 00:08:24,085
A claw.

104
00:08:24,090 --> 00:08:26,990
That's no claw, by the Gods.

105
00:08:26,992 --> 00:08:28,562
It's a tooth.

106
00:08:28,560 --> 00:08:31,760
You want me to do battle
with that?

107
00:08:31,763 --> 00:08:34,303
Who else can we turn to?

108
00:08:34,298 --> 00:08:37,468
Did you... did you try
the Merydid sisters?

109
00:08:37,467 --> 00:08:38,367
What about Rimbog?

110
00:08:38,367 --> 00:08:42,397
I-I heard tell he
killed a dragon once.

111
00:08:42,404 --> 00:08:44,004
They're all dead.

112
00:08:44,005 --> 00:08:45,835
You're the only one left.

113
00:08:45,840 --> 00:08:52,110
It is a long way to Urland.

114
00:08:52,112 --> 00:08:56,782
Twice each year, at the spring
and autumn equinox,

115
00:08:56,782 --> 00:08:59,282
the king selects a new victim--

116
00:08:59,284 --> 00:09:01,024
virgins.

117
00:09:01,019 --> 00:09:03,119
A lottery.

118
00:09:03,121 --> 00:09:04,121
Barbaric.

119
00:09:04,122 --> 00:09:05,992
And in return,
this dragon--

120
00:09:05,990 --> 00:09:11,290
it leaves your villages
and crops unburned.

121
00:09:11,294 --> 00:09:13,264
Your king's

122
00:09:13,262 --> 00:09:15,532
made a pact
with a monster.

123
00:09:15,530 --> 00:09:17,330
Master, don't you think that...

124
00:09:17,331 --> 00:09:19,331
Silence.

125
00:09:19,333 --> 00:09:22,773
Are you afraid of dragons?

126
00:09:24,203 --> 00:09:25,243
No.

127
00:09:25,237 --> 00:09:27,137
In fact, if it weren't
for sorcerers,

128
00:09:27,138 --> 00:09:28,998
there wouldn't
be any dragons.

129
00:09:29,006 --> 00:09:32,136
Once the skies were
dotted with them.

130
00:09:32,142 --> 00:09:37,382
Magnificent horned backs,
leathern wings, soaring,

131
00:09:37,380 --> 00:09:39,910
in their hot breath wind.

132
00:09:39,915 --> 00:09:43,845
Oh, I know this
creature of yours--

133
00:09:44,785 --> 00:09:47,585
Vermithrax Pejorative.

134
00:09:47,587 --> 00:09:51,717
Look at these scales,
these ridges.

135
00:09:51,723 --> 00:09:52,863
When a dragon gets this old,

136
00:09:52,858 --> 00:09:57,558
it knows nothing but pain,
constant pain.

137
00:09:57,562 --> 00:10:01,702
He grows decrepit, crippled...

138
00:10:01,698 --> 00:10:03,628
pitiful...

139
00:10:03,633 --> 00:10:06,873
spiteful.

140
00:10:07,469 --> 00:10:10,239
Will you help us?

141
00:10:11,038 --> 00:10:12,398
There.

142
00:10:12,406 --> 00:10:13,296
Good.

143
00:10:13,306 --> 00:10:15,806
Now, let-let me go.

144
00:10:15,808 --> 00:10:17,438
Hmm.

145
00:10:17,442 --> 00:10:18,912
No.

146
00:10:18,910 --> 00:10:20,710
No, not...

147
00:10:20,711 --> 00:10:22,681
not a bit too heavy.

148
00:10:22,679 --> 00:10:26,709
I'll...
conquer the highest mountain.

149
00:10:26,715 --> 00:10:29,745
What say you, Galen?

150
00:10:30,550 --> 00:10:32,880
Speak up, boy.

151
00:10:32,885 --> 00:10:33,945
Hodge?

152
00:10:33,952 --> 00:10:37,652
Uh, if you say so, sir.

153
00:10:38,554 --> 00:10:40,344
When I've gone,

154
00:10:40,338 --> 00:10:42,118
see you keep your nose
in your books

155
00:10:42,124 --> 00:10:45,894
and your hands out
of my reagents.

156
00:10:45,893 --> 00:10:47,963
How far can
you get?

157
00:10:47,961 --> 00:10:49,361
A league

158
00:10:49,362 --> 00:10:52,062
or two?

159
00:10:52,063 --> 00:10:54,763
I'm not worried about the road.

160
00:10:57,535 --> 00:10:58,895
Tyrian.

161
00:10:58,903 --> 00:11:01,003
(<i> bird shrieks</i> )

162
00:11:01,005 --> 00:11:03,135
Good morrow.

163
00:11:04,141 --> 00:11:05,971
(<i> wind whistling</i> )

164
00:11:05,976 --> 00:11:07,806
VALERIAN:
What do you want?

165
00:11:07,811 --> 00:11:09,541
(<i> chuckling</i> ):
No...

166
00:11:09,546 --> 00:11:10,906
young master Valerian.

167
00:11:10,914 --> 00:11:13,514
The question is,
what do<i> you</i> want

168
00:11:13,516 --> 00:11:15,476
so far from home?

169
00:11:15,484 --> 00:11:17,324
We're not afraid of you.

170
00:11:17,319 --> 00:11:18,519
Give us the road.

171
00:11:18,520 --> 00:11:20,490
Why, the road is yours,

172
00:11:20,488 --> 00:11:22,688
all the way to Urland.

173
00:11:22,690 --> 00:11:24,220
It's a long journey, isn't it?

174
00:11:24,224 --> 00:11:27,834
But when you're in search
of a sorcerer,

175
00:11:27,827 --> 00:11:31,227
I suppose
no distance is too great.

176
00:11:31,229 --> 00:11:32,289
Say nothing.

177
00:11:32,296 --> 00:11:35,596
TYRIAN:
And here, we
have the mystical

178
00:11:35,599 --> 00:11:36,629
presence himself.

179
00:11:36,633 --> 00:11:38,233
You best keep your distance.

180
00:11:38,234 --> 00:11:39,874
And your manners.

181
00:11:39,868 --> 00:11:42,768
If he's ready to lay
a dragon in its grave,

182
00:11:42,770 --> 00:11:46,170
he's nothing
to fear from me.

183
00:11:46,173 --> 00:11:49,913
I've no more love
for that creature than you lot.

184
00:11:49,910 --> 00:11:52,310
Nor has the king.

185
00:11:52,312 --> 00:11:53,412
But...

186
00:11:53,413 --> 00:11:55,053
before you stir things up,

187
00:11:55,047 --> 00:11:56,807
don't you think
it will be a good idea

188
00:11:56,815 --> 00:12:00,975
to find out if you've got
the right man for the job?

189
00:12:00,985 --> 00:12:05,185
Aha, so it's a test
you're looking for.

190
00:12:05,189 --> 00:12:06,789
We don't do tests.

191
00:12:06,790 --> 00:12:09,290
Oh, I'm sure you don't.

192
00:12:10,493 --> 00:12:11,693
(<i> splash</i> )

193
00:12:11,694 --> 00:12:13,594
They never do tests.

194
00:12:13,595 --> 00:12:15,125
Not many real deeds, either.

195
00:12:15,129 --> 00:12:18,599
Oh, conversation with
your grandmother's shade

196
00:12:18,599 --> 00:12:19,699
in a darkened room,

197
00:12:19,700 --> 00:12:21,670
the odd love
potion or two,

198
00:12:21,667 --> 00:12:23,627
but comes a doubter,
why then, it's the wrong day,

199
00:12:23,636 --> 00:12:28,206
the planets are not in line,
the entrails are not favorable.

200
00:12:28,207 --> 00:12:29,607
We don't do tests.

201
00:12:29,608 --> 00:12:30,938
We've got no doubts.

202
00:12:30,942 --> 00:12:32,372
We require no tests.

203
00:12:32,376 --> 00:12:34,176
And you're not going to get one.

204
00:12:34,177 --> 00:12:34,937
Enough. Here.

205
00:12:34,944 --> 00:12:38,784
Put this in
the conjuring room.

206
00:12:38,780 --> 00:12:40,610
Go to the iron box.

207
00:12:40,615 --> 00:12:43,515
Bring me the
dagger within.

208
00:12:43,517 --> 00:12:47,417
The<i> dagger.</i>
Be quick.

209
00:12:49,388 --> 00:12:53,218
You shall have your test.

210
00:12:53,224 --> 00:12:56,164
(<i> door squeaks</i> )

211
00:13:02,466 --> 00:13:05,496
(<i> clattering</i> )

212
00:13:05,502 --> 00:13:08,402
ULRICH:
Where are you, boy?

213
00:13:08,404 --> 00:13:10,544
I'm waiting.

214
00:13:10,539 --> 00:13:13,409
It's not this one, is it?

215
00:13:13,408 --> 00:13:15,308
The very one.

216
00:13:15,309 --> 00:13:17,909
Let it fall.

217
00:13:50,910 --> 00:13:57,950
(<i> chanting spell in Latin</i> )

218
00:14:01,053 --> 00:14:04,093
(<i> bird squawks</i> )

219
00:14:06,791 --> 00:14:09,391
(<i> bird squawking</i> )

220
00:14:12,596 --> 00:14:14,386
(<i> screeching</i> )

221
00:14:16,498 --> 00:14:17,758
GALEN:
No!

222
00:14:17,765 --> 00:14:18,395
Go on.

223
00:14:18,398 --> 00:14:19,658
Somebody
stop him!

224
00:14:19,665 --> 00:14:20,655
Don't worry.

225
00:14:20,666 --> 00:14:21,526
Please!

226
00:14:21,533 --> 00:14:25,033
You can't hurt me.

227
00:14:25,036 --> 00:14:29,466
(<i> horse neighs</i> )

228
00:14:39,950 --> 00:14:42,220
(<i> grunting</i> )

229
00:14:51,493 --> 00:14:53,563
(<i> grunting</i> )

230
00:15:16,449 --> 00:15:19,319
(<i> metal clinking</i> )

231
00:17:03,088 --> 00:17:05,988
Magical powers, indeed.

232
00:17:05,990 --> 00:17:09,160
Look at you now...
magical ashes.

233
00:17:09,159 --> 00:17:12,559
(<i> birds squawking</i> )

234
00:17:56,472 --> 00:18:01,012
(<i> rumbling</i> )

235
00:18:03,511 --> 00:18:07,751
(<i> soft buzzing</i> )

236
00:18:31,671 --> 00:18:34,201
(<i> buzzing</i> )

237
00:18:44,482 --> 00:18:47,552
Hodge...

238
00:18:47,551 --> 00:18:51,151
Hodge!

239
00:19:18,280 --> 00:19:22,720
HODGE:
The kindest lord a man
could ever wish for

240
00:19:22,717 --> 00:19:25,417
and now he's gone.

241
00:19:25,419 --> 00:19:26,989
Ye gods.

242
00:19:26,986 --> 00:19:28,546
You'd think he could
boil his own eggs

243
00:19:28,555 --> 00:19:32,055
at the snap of
a finger, but no...

244
00:19:32,058 --> 00:19:34,218
had old Hodge to do it.

245
00:19:34,226 --> 00:19:36,186
Up at 5:00 every morning,

246
00:19:36,194 --> 00:19:39,464
clearing out the cages,
emptying the slops.

247
00:19:39,463 --> 00:19:43,403
Never once a "thank you"
or a pat on the back.

248
00:19:43,399 --> 00:19:46,569
(<i> choked up</i> ):
I shall miss it.

249
00:19:46,568 --> 00:19:47,568
I do already.

250
00:19:47,569 --> 00:19:49,389
No, you don't.

251
00:19:49,386 --> 00:19:51,196
All you think about
is your tricks

252
00:19:51,205 --> 00:19:52,235
and your knavery.

253
00:19:52,239 --> 00:19:54,609
But you don't
pull any wool

254
00:19:54,608 --> 00:19:55,938
over these
old eyes.

255
00:19:55,942 --> 00:19:58,282
You'll have to
walk a long way

256
00:19:58,277 --> 00:20:00,777
before you fill
his shoes.

257
00:20:00,779 --> 00:20:02,649
You mark my words.

258
00:20:02,647 --> 00:20:07,347
What's the matter, Hodge--
pack too heavy?

259
00:20:07,351 --> 00:20:08,851
Huh?

260
00:20:08,852 --> 00:20:10,822
Uh...

261
00:20:10,820 --> 00:20:12,620
No! Don't!

262
00:20:12,621 --> 00:20:13,801
Don't!

263
00:20:13,805 --> 00:20:14,985
(<i> mutters</i> )

264
00:20:14,990 --> 00:20:16,890
I<i> need</i> that.

265
00:20:16,891 --> 00:20:18,621
Give it back to me.

266
00:20:18,626 --> 00:20:19,826
T-This way.

267
00:20:19,827 --> 00:20:20,657
No, no...

268
00:20:20,661 --> 00:20:22,891
I think you're too warm.

269
00:20:23,663 --> 00:20:25,053
Stop it!

270
00:20:25,046 --> 00:20:26,426
Out of respect
for the master.

271
00:20:26,431 --> 00:20:31,971
I have as much respect for
the master as anyone, old man.

272
00:20:31,969 --> 00:20:34,669
But then again, I'm master now.

273
00:20:40,175 --> 00:20:43,875
I left my farm...
and for what?

274
00:20:43,878 --> 00:20:46,248
For a cremation,
that's what.

275
00:20:46,247 --> 00:20:50,947
All because someone
said "find a magician."

276
00:20:50,951 --> 00:20:54,121
Not a local fellow,
an import.

277
00:20:54,120 --> 00:20:57,290
Some hundred
leagues from home.

278
00:20:57,289 --> 00:21:01,519
An all-powerful
necromancer.

279
00:21:01,526 --> 00:21:02,886
(<i> scoffs</i> )

280
00:21:02,894 --> 00:21:04,494
That's some
necromancer.

281
00:21:04,495 --> 00:21:07,195
Hold your tongue,
Greil. Eat.

282
00:21:07,198 --> 00:21:11,498
I'll not eat.
I'm not hungry.

283
00:21:12,969 --> 00:21:15,149
He's right.

284
00:21:15,153 --> 00:21:17,343
I brought us here
for nothing.

285
00:21:17,339 --> 00:21:20,839
(<i> rumbling</i> )

286
00:21:20,842 --> 00:21:24,012
(<i> sizzling</i> )

287
00:21:25,212 --> 00:21:26,282
What is it?

288
00:21:26,279 --> 00:21:30,209
Who's there?

289
00:21:30,215 --> 00:21:33,615
(<i> speaking Latin</i> )

290
00:21:33,617 --> 00:21:35,147
Good morrow.

291
00:21:35,151 --> 00:21:36,421
Peace be with you.

292
00:21:36,418 --> 00:21:39,518
What do<i> you</i> want?

293
00:21:39,521 --> 00:21:41,921
My lord Ulrich is no longer.

294
00:21:41,923 --> 00:21:46,393
All that you asked of him,
you may now expect of me.

295
00:21:46,393 --> 00:21:50,763
The dangers he would face,
I will now conquer.

296
00:21:50,763 --> 00:21:57,003
The task he would undertake,
I will now fulfill.

297
00:21:58,035 --> 00:21:59,665
I'm Galen Brandwardyn...

298
00:21:59,669 --> 00:22:05,009
inheritor of Ulrich's craft
and knowledge...

299
00:22:05,007 --> 00:22:08,777
and I am the sorcerer you seek.

300
00:22:15,817 --> 00:22:19,447
(<i> drum beats</i> )

301
00:22:33,800 --> 00:22:36,100
(<i> neighing</i> )

302
00:22:36,102 --> 00:22:36,972
Whoa!

303
00:22:36,969 --> 00:22:38,969
(<i> neighing</i> )

304
00:22:39,738 --> 00:22:41,468
Close enough.

305
00:22:41,473 --> 00:22:44,373
Bring her out.

306
00:22:44,842 --> 00:22:46,512
(<i> gasping</i> )

307
00:22:46,510 --> 00:22:48,780
(<i> horse neighing</i> )

308
00:22:53,983 --> 00:22:56,883
(<i> neighing</i> )

309
00:23:02,589 --> 00:23:04,659
(<i> whimpering cry</i> )

310
00:23:04,657 --> 00:23:06,987
MAN:
Now be it known
throughout the kingdom

311
00:23:06,992 --> 00:23:10,062
that this maiden,
having lawfully been chosen

312
00:23:10,061 --> 00:23:13,061
by a deed of fortune
and destiny

313
00:23:13,064 --> 00:23:14,604
shall hereby give up her life

314
00:23:14,598 --> 00:23:17,228
for the greater good of Urland!

315
00:23:17,233 --> 00:23:20,233
(<i> deep rumbling</i> )

316
00:23:20,236 --> 00:23:22,536
By this act shall be satisfied

317
00:23:22,538 --> 00:23:25,608
the powers that dwell
underground!

318
00:23:25,607 --> 00:23:27,667
(<i> people yelling</i> )

319
00:23:27,675 --> 00:23:29,505
(<i> horse whinnies</i> )

320
00:23:29,510 --> 00:23:32,180
In gratitude of this sacrifice,

321
00:23:32,179 --> 00:23:33,579
His Majesty declares

322
00:23:33,580 --> 00:23:35,350
the father, a plowman

323
00:23:35,348 --> 00:23:36,978
to be free
of obligations

324
00:23:36,982 --> 00:23:39,352
for a period
not to exceed

325
00:23:39,351 --> 00:23:41,181
five years!

326
00:23:41,186 --> 00:23:44,816
(<i> neighing</i> )

327
00:23:44,822 --> 00:23:47,122
Duly ordained...

328
00:23:48,624 --> 00:23:51,794
(<i> metal clinking</i> )

329
00:23:54,295 --> 00:23:57,625
(<i> grunting</i> )

330
00:24:01,367 --> 00:24:03,867
(<i> gasps</i> )

331
00:24:06,972 --> 00:24:09,842
(<i> grunting</i> )

332
00:24:15,146 --> 00:24:18,976
(<i> whinnies</i> )

333
00:24:31,094 --> 00:24:34,534
(<i> distant roaring</i> )

334
00:24:35,564 --> 00:24:41,874
(<i> grunting</i> )

335
00:24:44,371 --> 00:24:47,211
(<i> roar</i> )

336
00:24:56,649 --> 00:24:59,119
(<i> panting</i> )

337
00:25:02,354 --> 00:25:04,024
(<i> ferocious growling</i> )

338
00:25:04,022 --> 00:25:08,462
(<i> whinnies</i> )

339
00:25:09,693 --> 00:25:11,593
(<i> panicked grunts</i> )

340
00:25:11,594 --> 00:25:12,864
(<i> growling</i> )

341
00:25:12,861 --> 00:25:16,061
(<i> panting</i> )

342
00:25:20,067 --> 00:25:22,527
(<i> grunting</i> )

343
00:25:22,536 --> 00:25:25,136
(<i> growl</i> )

344
00:25:28,641 --> 00:25:33,081
(<i> roaring</i> )

345
00:25:33,078 --> 00:25:37,178
(<i> panting</i> )

346
00:25:39,116 --> 00:25:41,916
(<i> gasps</i> )

347
00:25:51,127 --> 00:25:53,957
(<i> growling</i> )

348
00:25:53,963 --> 00:25:56,103
(<i> whinnies</i> )

349
00:26:00,535 --> 00:26:03,765
(<i> screams</i> )

350
00:26:18,818 --> 00:26:20,648
(<i> water dripping</i> )

351
00:26:20,653 --> 00:26:23,053
(<i> gasping</i> )

352
00:26:24,455 --> 00:26:27,555
(<i> roaring</i> )

353
00:26:27,558 --> 00:26:29,658
(<i> screaming</i> )

354
00:26:29,660 --> 00:26:32,730
(<i> gasping</i> )

355
00:26:35,363 --> 00:26:39,303
(<i> birds chirping</i> )

356
00:26:55,715 --> 00:26:57,775
What have you got there, Hodge?

357
00:26:57,783 --> 00:26:59,683
None of your business.

358
00:26:59,684 --> 00:27:01,254
A little gold, eh?

359
00:27:01,251 --> 00:27:02,821
What do you say I
change it into lead?

360
00:27:02,820 --> 00:27:04,690
Save your jokes
for someone else.

361
00:27:04,688 --> 00:27:10,058
For me, I do not care
for braggarts or frauds.

362
00:27:11,693 --> 00:27:12,793
I'm no fraud.

363
00:27:12,794 --> 00:27:16,504
Well, then, upstart.
Whatever pleases you.

364
00:27:16,497 --> 00:27:19,097
Look, Hodge,
nobody forced you

365
00:27:19,099 --> 00:27:20,549
to come along.

366
00:27:20,549 --> 00:27:21,999
I know I came on my own feet.
Well, all right.

367
00:27:22,001 --> 00:27:27,271
We each do the Master's bidding
in our own way.

368
00:27:40,618 --> 00:27:42,578
VALERIAN:
What are you doing?

369
00:27:42,586 --> 00:27:45,916
Don't come in!

370
00:27:46,389 --> 00:27:48,289
How's the water?

371
00:27:49,057 --> 00:27:51,317
It's cold.

372
00:27:55,695 --> 00:28:00,825
I prefer to swim alone,
if you don't mind.

373
00:28:07,672 --> 00:28:10,672
Stay away.

374
00:28:15,712 --> 00:28:17,982
Look, Sire,
isn't that...?

375
00:28:17,980 --> 00:28:19,250
Yes.

376
00:28:19,247 --> 00:28:20,507
The old retainer
from Cragganmore.

377
00:28:20,515 --> 00:28:21,605
What's he
doing here?

378
00:28:21,616 --> 00:28:23,816
Filling in
for his chief, I reckon.

379
00:28:23,818 --> 00:28:27,788
Are you going to
allow that, sir?

380
00:28:30,257 --> 00:28:33,117
Bring me my bow.

381
00:28:35,827 --> 00:28:39,657
No, I'm not going
to say anything.

382
00:28:39,664 --> 00:28:41,634
I don't blame you.

383
00:28:41,632 --> 00:28:43,632
I was careless.

384
00:28:43,634 --> 00:28:45,434
A silly woman!

385
00:28:45,435 --> 00:28:47,665
Oh. I-I knew
the moment I saw you.

386
00:28:47,670 --> 00:28:50,200
I've known
the whole time.

387
00:28:50,205 --> 00:28:52,735
You never knew a thing.

388
00:28:52,740 --> 00:28:54,310
No one's known.

389
00:28:54,308 --> 00:28:57,378
Not since I was born.

390
00:28:57,377 --> 00:28:59,607
The lottery--

391
00:28:59,612 --> 00:29:03,112
daughters are chosen,
sons are not.

392
00:29:03,115 --> 00:29:05,325
That's right.

393
00:29:05,333 --> 00:29:07,553
Unless you happen
to be the daughter of the king.

394
00:29:07,552 --> 00:29:10,072
What do you mean?

395
00:29:10,070 --> 00:29:12,590
If you're rich enough,
your name never goes in.

396
00:29:12,590 --> 00:29:17,230
My father is poor.

397
00:29:17,227 --> 00:29:20,357
So are a lot of fathers.

398
00:29:27,436 --> 00:29:31,766
(<i> wings fluttering loudly</i> )

399
00:30:02,603 --> 00:30:08,413
(<i> hooves pounding</i> )

400
00:30:17,983 --> 00:30:20,223
No!

401
00:30:20,218 --> 00:30:22,848
No!

402
00:30:24,588 --> 00:30:26,588
No!

403
00:30:28,324 --> 00:30:30,724
Hodge!

404
00:30:30,726 --> 00:30:33,326
Hodge!

405
00:30:36,163 --> 00:30:38,233
Hodge.

406
00:30:41,434 --> 00:30:43,134
(<i> moaning softly</i> )

407
00:30:43,135 --> 00:30:46,265
Galen, can you hear me?

408
00:30:46,271 --> 00:30:47,671
I hear you.

409
00:30:47,672 --> 00:30:51,142
Do you know
somebody shot me,

410
00:30:51,142 --> 00:30:52,882
but I can still talk.

411
00:30:52,877 --> 00:30:56,307
There's something
that needs to be done.

412
00:30:56,313 --> 00:30:57,113
I know.

413
00:30:57,113 --> 00:30:59,653
No, no, not the dragon.

414
00:30:59,648 --> 00:31:02,278
The Master's ashes!

415
00:31:02,283 --> 00:31:04,223
Here!

416
00:31:04,218 --> 00:31:04,918
I'm sorry.

417
00:31:04,918 --> 00:31:08,018
You'll have to
peel it loose.

418
00:31:08,021 --> 00:31:09,691
(<i> moans</i> )

419
00:31:09,689 --> 00:31:12,119
Burning water.

420
00:31:12,124 --> 00:31:13,594
What?

421
00:31:13,592 --> 00:31:15,892
Find the lake.

422
00:31:15,894 --> 00:31:17,294
Throw it in.

423
00:31:17,295 --> 00:31:20,355
Hodge, what are you
doing with this?

424
00:31:20,364 --> 00:31:24,204
Burning... water.

425
00:31:24,900 --> 00:31:27,970
Hodge, don't die.

426
00:31:27,969 --> 00:31:29,099
Listen to me.

427
00:31:29,103 --> 00:31:31,773
You're not going
to die.

428
00:31:31,772 --> 00:31:36,472
(<i> chanting spell</i> )

429
00:31:36,476 --> 00:31:39,306
(<i> sizzling, gasps</i> )

430
00:32:49,515 --> 00:32:52,115
Urland.

431
00:34:06,057 --> 00:34:06,917
Come on.

432
00:34:06,924 --> 00:34:08,194
Don't slow down here.

433
00:34:08,191 --> 00:34:10,161
Is the whole
kingdom like this?

434
00:34:10,159 --> 00:34:13,729
No. We're near
the lair.

435
00:34:13,728 --> 00:34:15,558
The lair?

436
00:34:15,563 --> 00:34:16,703
Where is it?

437
00:34:16,697 --> 00:34:18,357
Doesn't matter.

438
00:34:18,365 --> 00:34:19,655
Show me.

439
00:34:19,666 --> 00:34:21,796
Where?

440
00:34:21,801 --> 00:34:22,801
We're in no danger,

441
00:34:22,802 --> 00:34:25,102
if we just pass
though quickly.

442
00:34:25,104 --> 00:34:27,544
I want to see it.

443
00:34:28,139 --> 00:34:29,669
(<i> rumbling</i> )

444
00:34:29,673 --> 00:34:31,643
Greil!

445
00:34:38,014 --> 00:34:41,124
Taffiet! Taffiet!

446
00:35:11,279 --> 00:35:13,779
Are there other entrances?

447
00:35:13,781 --> 00:35:14,711
No.

448
00:35:14,715 --> 00:35:17,545
One's enough.

449
00:35:23,623 --> 00:35:25,163
Don't be a fool!

450
00:35:25,157 --> 00:35:27,987
You'll provoke it!

451
00:35:27,993 --> 00:35:31,563
How do you know it's in there?

452
00:35:35,900 --> 00:35:37,400
VALERIAN:
Go on, then.

453
00:35:37,401 --> 00:35:39,431
Get yourself
burned alive.

454
00:35:39,436 --> 00:35:42,566
What a fine trick that will be.

455
00:35:45,775 --> 00:35:50,305
(<i> bones creaking</i> )

456
00:36:09,697 --> 00:36:14,327
(<i> low rumbling</i> )

457
00:36:29,148 --> 00:36:33,918
(<i> loud roar</i> )

458
00:36:33,918 --> 00:36:35,528
Vermithrax.

459
00:36:35,535 --> 00:36:37,145
(<i> echoing</i> ):
...thrax... thrax... thrax...

460
00:36:37,153 --> 00:36:41,163
(<i> rumbling growl</i> )

461
00:36:46,161 --> 00:36:50,301
(<i> coughing</i> )

462
00:36:53,967 --> 00:36:58,167
(<i> water dripping</i> )

463
00:36:59,304 --> 00:37:02,544
(<i> wind whistling</i> )

464
00:37:05,809 --> 00:37:10,949
(<i> chanting spell</i> )

465
00:38:04,500 --> 00:38:05,370
No!

466
00:38:05,367 --> 00:38:07,697
(<i> yelling spell</i> )

467
00:38:47,141 --> 00:38:51,341
(<i> small rocks falling</i> )

468
00:39:04,791 --> 00:39:07,591
That's a wizard.

469
00:39:08,961 --> 00:39:11,361
He's done it!

470
00:39:22,506 --> 00:39:24,336
(<i> people shouting and laughing</i> )

471
00:39:24,341 --> 00:39:27,541
(<i> music playing</i> )

472
00:39:36,152 --> 00:39:40,492
(<i> cheering</i> )

473
00:39:43,892 --> 00:39:47,792
(<i> laughing</i> )

474
00:39:54,268 --> 00:39:57,998
(<i> exclamations of delight</i> )

475
00:40:18,792 --> 00:40:21,562
Put that away.

476
00:40:24,496 --> 00:40:27,396
What if you were seen?

477
00:40:30,267 --> 00:40:33,267
(<i> laughing and talking</i> )

478
00:40:33,270 --> 00:40:38,040
(<i> all grow silent</i> )

479
00:41:25,287 --> 00:41:27,017
Musicians.

480
00:41:31,325 --> 00:41:36,025
(<i> playing medieval dance tune</i> )

481
00:42:05,224 --> 00:42:09,594
(<i> crowd murmuring</i> )

482
00:42:13,999 --> 00:42:15,669
The damnedest thing
is she was twice the man

483
00:42:15,667 --> 00:42:20,337
of anyone else in the village,
and now she's twice the woman.

484
00:42:20,337 --> 00:42:24,907
Would that I was as
clever as her father.

485
00:42:26,042 --> 00:42:27,642
Come now, Greil,

486
00:42:27,643 --> 00:42:29,513
don't begrudge
a life spared.

487
00:42:29,511 --> 00:42:33,511
No, I... I
begrudge nothing.

488
00:42:33,514 --> 00:42:37,284
But I... I wonder
at what we have seen

489
00:42:37,284 --> 00:42:39,124
and how it was done.

490
00:42:39,119 --> 00:42:41,049
You were there.
Aye.

491
00:42:41,054 --> 00:42:43,374
But isn't it strange?

492
00:42:43,372 --> 00:42:45,692
At the very moment that
the beast was put down,

493
00:42:45,691 --> 00:42:49,391
there should be a holy
man in the village.

494
00:42:49,394 --> 00:42:51,164
Now, isn't that strange?

495
00:42:51,162 --> 00:42:52,732
(<i> music playing, laughing</i> )

496
00:42:52,730 --> 00:42:56,700
(<i> dog barking</i> )

497
00:42:58,802 --> 00:43:01,802
Could the Christian God
bring down a whole mountain?

498
00:43:01,805 --> 00:43:02,695
Is it possible, Father?

499
00:43:02,705 --> 00:43:06,265
Of course it is, my
son-- and why not?

500
00:43:19,086 --> 00:43:22,586
(<i> music stops</i> )

501
00:43:40,339 --> 00:43:41,869
A celebration.

502
00:43:41,873 --> 00:43:47,683
(<i> chuckles</i> ):
Well, don't stop
on my account.

503
00:43:48,645 --> 00:43:51,405
Musicians...

504
00:43:51,414 --> 00:43:54,084
more music.

505
00:43:56,417 --> 00:43:57,677
A toast...

506
00:43:57,684 --> 00:44:01,094
To the deed
of the day!

507
00:44:02,721 --> 00:44:04,051
GREIL:
What would

508
00:44:04,055 --> 00:44:05,985
you have of us?

509
00:44:05,990 --> 00:44:07,690
With you?

510
00:44:07,691 --> 00:44:09,621
Not a thing.

511
00:44:09,626 --> 00:44:12,926
It's this one.

512
00:44:14,596 --> 00:44:18,726
The king would meet our
new-found benefactor

513
00:44:18,733 --> 00:44:20,303
and offer his gratitude

514
00:44:20,301 --> 00:44:22,401
to the one man
who has succeeded

515
00:44:22,403 --> 00:44:26,913
where so many
have failed.

516
00:44:26,907 --> 00:44:29,667
What sort of gratitude?

517
00:44:29,676 --> 00:44:31,676
A knife in the belly?

518
00:44:31,678 --> 00:44:33,438
Arrow in the chest?

519
00:44:33,446 --> 00:44:35,646
My young friend,

520
00:44:35,648 --> 00:44:39,448
I would as soon dispatch
you as I did the rest,

521
00:44:39,450 --> 00:44:42,150
and for the
same reason...

522
00:44:42,152 --> 00:44:45,592
but His Majesty would
have a cozy little chat

523
00:44:45,588 --> 00:44:48,658
and commands otherwise.

524
00:44:48,657 --> 00:44:50,957
(<i> chickens squawking</i> )
Hyah!

525
00:44:58,899 --> 00:45:02,369
Behold! Eggs fit for a king!

526
00:45:02,369 --> 00:45:06,039
(<i> clears throat</i> )

527
00:45:06,038 --> 00:45:08,488
Right.

528
00:45:08,489 --> 00:45:10,939
How many of you
have ever seen a table fly?

529
00:45:10,941 --> 00:45:13,161
None of you.

530
00:45:13,159 --> 00:45:15,379
None of you have ever seen
a table fly.

531
00:45:15,378 --> 00:45:18,148
Stand back.

532
00:45:20,215 --> 00:45:25,145
(<i> chants spell</i> )

533
00:45:30,791 --> 00:45:33,461
(<i> chants spell</i> )

534
00:45:46,439 --> 00:45:47,809
(<i> dog barks</i> )

535
00:45:47,807 --> 00:45:50,307
(<i> sighs</i> )

536
00:45:52,210 --> 00:45:53,740
Sorry, sorry.

537
00:45:53,744 --> 00:45:54,894
Sorry.

538
00:45:54,894 --> 00:45:56,044
KING:
Now, that'll do.
I really can do this.

